   <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pb-16 md:pb-24"><div class="max-w-3xl prose">
     <h2>Why the right documentation matters</h2>
     <p>A generic note that says "John has ADHD" is not enough. For disability claims, employers, schools, and the SSA need specific information about <strong>functional limitations</strong> -- how your ADHD actually affects your ability to work, learn, or manage daily life.</p>
     <h2>What a strong doctor's note includes</h2>
     <h3>Essential elements for disability claims</h3>
     <ol><li><strong>Provider credentials:</strong> The doctor's license number, specialty, and contact information</li><li><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Formal ADHD diagnosis with date and diagnostic criteria used (e.g., DSM-5)</li><li><strong>Treatment history:</strong> Medications prescribed, therapy, and response to treatment</li><li><strong>Functional limitations:</strong> Specific ways ADHD affects daily functioning -- not just "has trouble concentrating" but "cannot complete multi-step tasks without written instructions and frequent check-ins"</li><li><strong>Recommended accommodations:</strong> Specific, practical suggestions</li><li><strong>Duration and prognosis:</strong> How long the condition is expected to last and expected outcomes</li></ol>
     <h2>How to talk to your doctor about it</h2>
     <h3>What to bring to your appointment</h3>
     <p>Many doctors are unfamiliar with writing disability documentation for ADHD. Come prepared:</p>
     <ul><li>Bring a <strong>specific list</strong> of your work or school challenges</li><li>Bring a copy of your <strong>job description</strong> or academic requirements</li><li>Bring a list of <strong>accommodations you think would help</strong></li><li>Explain <strong>why the documentation is needed</strong> (HR request, 504 evaluation, SSDI application)</li><li>If the doctor is hesitant, ask them to document your <strong>observed symptoms and functional limitations</strong> rather than making legal conclusions</li></ul>
     <h2>Sample letter structure</h2>
     <h3>How a strong disability letter is organized</h3>
     <p>While not a template to copy, here is what a strong letter looks like structurally:</p>
     <blockquote><p>[Provider letterhead]</p><p>To Whom It May Concern:</p><p>[Patient name] has been under my care since [date] for Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD), diagnosed per DSM-5 criteria. Despite ongoing treatment including [medication/therapy], [patient] continues to experience the following functional limitations: [specific examples].</p><p>I recommend the following accommodations to address these limitations: [list]. These accommodations are medically necessary to allow [patient] to perform the essential functions of [their job / their education].</p></blockquote>
     <h2>What if your doctor refuses?</h2>
     <h3>Alternative documentation options</h3>
     <p>Some doctors are reluctant to write disability documentation, especially for ADHD. If this happens:</p>
     <ul><li><strong>Ask why.</strong> Understand their concern -- is it about the specific accommodation requested, or documentation in general?</li><li><strong>Seek a second opinion.</strong> A psychiatrist or clinical psychologist who specializes in ADHD may be more familiar with disability documentation</li><li><strong>Get a neuropsychological evaluation.</strong> A formal evaluation provides objective evidence of functional limitations</li><li><strong>Remember:</strong> Your employer or school cannot require you to see a specific doctor</li></ul>
   </div></section>
